<HEADLINE>
<P>
THEATER REVIEWS; 'OZ' WORKS SOME MAGIC IN GLENDORA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LYNNE HEFFLEY, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Theater-goers had to dodge a light drizzle to get there, only a few snowflakes 
fell during the poppy scene, Toto stole the show with every wag of his stubby 
tail and coy spotlights played hide-and-seek with the cast, but the familiar 
story worked its charm and the bubbly national touring production of "The 
Wizard of Oz" was a major crowd-pleaser at Haugh Performing Arts Center in 
Glendora on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 The show moves to the Cerritos Center for the Performing Arts today and 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
 This recreation of the MGM film classic, with (limited) Flying by Foy and 
added material that was cut from the movie, is the Royal Shakespeare Company 
version that has been touring for several years. But judging from the vocal 
enthusiasm of Thursday's audience, its appeal for young and old is 
undiminished. 
</P>
<P>
 And, although the professional cast, directed by Richard Ericson and headed by 
Kim Smith as Dorothy, won't make you forget the originals, the actors do a 
respectable job with both the Harold Arlen/E.Y. Harburg movie score and John 
Dietrich's stage choreography, particularly in the riotous "Jitterbug" number, 
not seen in the film. 
</P>
<P>
 The spare bus-and-truck look of Kent Homchick's sets is made up for by 
designer John Carver Sullivan's lavish, colorful costumes and the rib-tickling 
puppets and creatures created by Big Nazo Studio, including assorted comic 
Munchkins and the great Oz himself, a giant head with rolling eyes. 
</P>
<P>
 Terrific ensemble numbers and the small but spirited orchestra, led by 
conductor Kelsey Halbert, add excitement and depth. The elaborate lighting 
design by Tom Sturge would too, if not for Thursday's frequent glitches, one of 
which made the liquidation of the Wicked Witch (Ellen Martin) decidedly 
anticlimactic. 
</P>
<P>
 Besides Smith and Martin, the cast includes Matthew MacDougall as the 
Scarecrow, Brad Wills as the Tin Man and scene-stealer Lennie Watts as the 
comic Cowardly Lion. Alezander M. Oleksij is the fraudulent but kindly Wizard 
and Debora J. Rascoe doubles as Aunt Em and a somewhat raffish Glinda. 
</P>
<P>
 * "The Wizard of Oz," Cerritos Center for the Performing Arts, 12700 Center 
Court Drive, today 2 and 8 p.m.; Sunday, 2 and 7 p.m. $16-$30; (310) 916-8500. 
Running time: 2 hours, 15 minutes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Play Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020594-0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 010528 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
February 5, 1994, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part F; Page 7; Column 1; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
262 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
JAZZ REVIEWS; ELLINGTON WORK CAPS UNEVEN PROGRAM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LEONARD FEATHER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra, heard Thursday at the Wadsworth Theater, is 
essentially a repertory ensemble devoted to the works of Duke Ellington and 
other early giants, with only occasional bows to the present in the form of new 
works. 
</P>
<P>
 If the musicians paid attention to conductor Robert Sadin's odd gestures, they 
showed no evidence of it.In fact, the most effective conducting of the evening 
was seen when he yielded to trumpeter Jon Faddis, whose leading and playing on 
Dizzy Gillespie's "Things to Come" was one of the evening's few highlights.  
</P>
<P>
 The orchestra, though tightly unified, had difficulty at times in capturing 
the spirit of Thelonious Monk, Charles Mingus and the other pioneers -- several 
of whom, incidentally, were not basically big-band figures.  
</P>
<P>
 The ensemble's music director, pianist Marcus Roberts, hammered away at an 
overlong original, later offering a less-than-inspired "Where or When." If his 
solos were the nadir of the evening, its zenith was reached with the closing 
Ellington piece, "Diminuendo and Crescendo in Blue." This magnificent work was 
interpreted superbly, with Joshua Redman in the tenor sax solo made famous by 
Paul Gonsalves. 
</P>
<P>
 It has been claimed that jazz repertory groups are needed to perform for young 
audiences some of the great works they never heard played by the originators. 
It should be borne in mind, though, that the Ellington Orchestra is still 
around, as is the admirable Basie Band. Credit the Lincoln Center Jazz 
Orchestra with good intentions that are not too often realized. LEONARD FEATHER 
</P>
</TEXT>
