<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: MORE RAIN FORECAST FOR COUNTY TODAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PATRICK McCARTNEY and BRENDA DAY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ventura County residents hoping to enjoy a weekend respite from rain should 
get out and enjoy the partly cloudy morning today, because the precipitation is 
forecast to start up again by this afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
 Between noon Thursday and Friday, coastal areas in Ventura County received up 
to three-quarters of an inch of rain, while the foothills were drenched with an 
inch from the storm, said National Weather Service meteorologist Bruce 
Entwistle. 
</P>
<P>
 And the latest rain, which could continue through Monday, is expected to bring 
colder temperatures, he said. Daytime highs could be in the 50s, and lows could 
fall to the lower 30s Sunday and Monday, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's going to be downright nippy for these parts," Entwistle said. 
</P>
<P>
 Rain totals for the season remained low despite the steady rain, Entwistle 
said. "Anything helps, but we're still behind," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 The rain combined with high winds to create problems for fishermen on three 
vessels, which became disabled or ran aground off Santa Cruz Island. The U.S. 
Coast Guard rescued seven fishermen from the boats. Two of the men were treated 
for hypothermia at Goleta Hospital in Santa Barbara. County Rainfall 
</P>
