<HEADLINE>
<P>
O.C. RELIGION NOTES / DAYE CLARK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAYE CLARK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The ASSIST ministry in Garden Grove has begun their Bridge of Friendship 
project linking 600,000 new Christian youths in the former Soviet Union to 
North American Christians.The project is in conjunction with the Christian 
Broadcasting Network of Virginia Beach, Va., who co-produced a television 
program called "What Are You Living For?" which was shown in the former Soviet 
Union. Many of the youths became Christians after viewing the program, then 
enrolled in a Bible correspondence course offered through CBN's office in Kiev. 
</P>
<P>
 Dan Wooding, founder and president of ASSIST (Aid to Special Saints in 
Strategic Times), is recruiting several thousand Canadian and American 
Christians to write to these youths. Those interested can call (714) 530-6598. 
</P>
